5B¶

Column Meanings:

pt - scalar transverse momentum. $\vec{p_T} \equiv (p_x,p_y)$, $p_T \equiv |p_T|$

eta - pseudorapidity. $\eta = ln cot{\frac{\theta}{2}}$ where $\theta$ is the polar angle.

phi - azimulathal angle of scattering. $\phi = \tan^{-1}{\frac{p_x}{p_y}}$

mass - invariant mass. Proportion of the mass that is independent of motion of the system. For a two particle collision this is given: $m = \sqrt{(E_1 + E_2)^2 - (\vec{p_1} + \vec{p_2})^2}$

ee2/ee3 - energies of the particles in the collision.

t_n - N-subjettiness. The degree to which jet radiation alligns along apecified subjet axes. Small values correspond to N or fewer subjets, large values correspond to N or more subjets.

t21 - ratio of t1 to t2, which "can identify boosted W/Z and Higgs bosons"

t32 - ratio of t3 to t2, which "is a successful boosted top discriminator"

KtDeltaR - $\Delta_R$ of two subjets within large-R jet

def plot_both(data1,data2,attribute1,attribute2=None,bins=40):
    
    if attribute2 == None:
        attribute2 = attribute1
        
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(1, 2)
    plt.rcParams["figure.figsize"] = (25,7)
    plt.tick_params(labelsize = 10)
    
    ax[0].hist(data1[attribute1],bins=bins)
    ax[1].hist(data2[attribute2],bins=bins)

    
    ax[0].set_title(f'{attribute1} histogram for Background dataset')
    ax[1].set_title(f'{attribute2} histogram for Higgs dataset')

    ax[0].set_yscale('log')
    ax[1].set_yscale('log')

1. Do all of the features provide discrimination power between signal and background?¶

Here I have plotted histograms for all features of the data for both the QCD simulated background data and the signal Higgs dataset. All are plotted in with a logarythmic y-axis to allow us to see detail in the data that would allow us to pick out difference in the signal in background.

In general, the Higgs data is less evenly spread and more narrowly located than the QCD data. This makes sense, as the Higgs data has the actual signal, and not the entire range of possible signals. Now I will remark on the discrimination power between signal and background for all the features:

pt - The range is the same for this feature, but the Higgs data is more peaked, and the QCD data is more smooth. Higgs data has a peak at 1100 and falls off on either side. It is concave up on the left of the peak and concave down on the right of the peak. This is distinct from the QCD which has a flat peak around 1075 and falls off much more smoothly on either side.

eta - Near identical, but the Higgs data is again less spread and more sharply peaked. The range of Higgs data here is less than the QCD. This does not provide a ton of discrimination power, as the shapes and ranges are close.

phi - Phi seems randomly distributed, or if there is a pattern I need to look deeper. So as of now I do not see it as useful for discrimination between signal and backgorund.

mass - A useful amount of discrimination power here. Mass in the QCD data is distributed from 0 to 800, while the Higgs data is only from 20 to 160. They have peaks around the same alue, but for whatever reason the Higgs data lacks the long tail of the expected background. This might be used to minimize our background.

ee2/ee3 - Both ee2 and ee3 have much smaller ranges in the Higgs data than the QCD data. I haven't got a clue why this is, but they seem to be smaller by a factor of 10. If this isn't a units difference or error, this provides great discrimination power, as the range of the Higgs data is much smaller and well defined.

d2 - They seem to have similar shapes, but the Higgs data only goes from 0 to 50, while the QCD data goes from 0 to 100, and has an outlier near 500. I think this provides some discrimination power, mainly due to the range maxing out at 50 rather than 100, not because of the outlier.

angularity - Again, similar shape, but the Higgs data is more narrowly distributed.

t1/t2 - A low amount of discrimination power, as the range and general shape of the data is nearly identical. They may look very different in a lograithmic plot however, as the shape of the tall off from the peak is near linear in the Higgs data, and more sloped in the QCD data.

t3 - I think there may be some use in this, as the QCD data is quite evenly distributed, while the Higgs data is more of a peak with a tail. They occupy the same range, but it may provide some discrimination power.

t21 - The plots are somewhat flipped. I am not sure the reason for this of the discrimination power it would provide.

t32 - The plots are nearly identical, so there is not much we can gather from this parameter in terms of discrimination power.

KtDeltaR - This feature has a good amount of discrimination power, as the peaks are different, range is different, and shape is different.

def correlation_plot(data,feature,bins=40,xmin=False,xmax=False):
    
    plt.rcParams["figure.figsize"] = (50,12)
    
    fig, ax = plt.subplots(2, 7)
    
    fig.suptitle(f'Correlation Plots for {feature}', fontsize=16)
    for a in range(7):
        for i in range(2):
            ax[i][a].hist2d(data[feature],data[higgs.keys()[a + 7*i]],bins=bins)
            ax[i][a].set_xlabel(feature)
            ax[i][a].set_ylabel(str(higgs.keys()[a + 7*i]))
            if xmin or xmax:
                ax[i][a].set_xlim(xmin,xmax)

2. Are there correlations among these features?¶

pt - pt has little to no correlation with any other features.

eta - eta only has correlation with angularity.

phi - phi has little to no correlation with any other features.

mass - mass has correlation with ee2, angularity, t1-3, and KtDeltaR. The correlation with ee2 is near linear, with higher mass correlating with lower ee2. The most notable correlation is mass with t3, where a higher mass will correspond with a lower t3. Higher mass also correlates to a higher KtDeltaR.

ee2 - Linear correlation with mass as stated earlier. There is a similar correlation with t1-3 as mass has, suggesting this feature and mass may be closely related. The correlation it has with kDeltaR is also similar to mass, but more linear.

ee3 - I recreated the plot for ee3, because the original has poor bounds that do not show the features of the data. With the new plot, we can see a slight correlation with mass and ee2 such that as ee3 rises, so does mass and ee2, in what looks somewhat logarythmic. There seems to be an opposite correlation with t1-3, but it is faint and hard to pick out.

d2 - I did the same for d2 as for ee3. Due to an outlier in the data, it is incredible hard to view on the original 2Dhists. The new plot shows many correlations. Correlations seem to have somewhat exponential curves. For mass,ee2, and KtDeltaR there is negative correlation; higher d2 means smaller mass/ee2. For t2,t3,t21, and t32, there is positive correlation.

At this point I have covered half of the plots, so I will only mention correlation with the remaining features:

angularity - no notable correlation

t1 - slight correlation with t2, t3, and t21, as you would expect.

t2 - t2 has correlation with t3, t21, t23, and KtDeltaR. KtDeltaR tends fowards 0 as t2 goes to ~0.8, which is the most likely value of t2.

t3 - similar correlations to t2.

3. Compute the expected discovery sensitivity (significance of the expected signal) by normalizing each sample appropriately (see 'expected yields' below).¶

As my expected yields from my QCD background is 2000, and my expected yields from my Higgs dataset is 50, I can approximate this with the probability of seeing a yeild of 2050 from a Poisson distribution with mean of 2000.

In [12]:
prob = stats.poisson.sf(2050,mu=2000)
In [13]:
prob
Out[13]:
0.12961287455491954

Converting this to a sigma value we get:

In [21]:
stats.norm.ppf(1-prob)
Out[21]:
1.1282230087754423

A sigma that is not all that unlikely.

4. Develop a plan to optimize the discovery sensitivity by applying selections to these features.¶

By using the correlations and discrimination powers I have outlined in this lab, I will be able to minimize the data I care about and ask a more specific question about the probability of seeing this specific dataset. I will mainly do this by throwing out parts of the background that are not relevant to my dataset, and I will determine this by looking at the descriminating features outlined in this lab.
